{"title_page": "Paterson (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2016 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Paterson\n| image = Paterson (film).png\n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Jim Jarmusch]]\n| producers = {{Plainlist|\n* Joshua Astrachan\n* Carter Logan\n}}\n| writer = Jim Jarmusch\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Adam Driver]]\n* [[Golshifteh Farahani]]\n* [[Barry Shabaka Henley]]\n* [[Method Man|Cliff Smith]]\n* Chasten Harmon\n* [[William Jackson Harper]]\n* [[Masatoshi Nagase]]\n}}<!--PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK-->\n| music = Carter Logan\n| cinematography = [[Frederick Elmes]]\n| editing = [[Affonso Gon\u00e7alves]]\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* K5 International\n* Le Pacte\n* Animal Kingdom\n* Inkjet Productions\n}}\n| distributors = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Amazon Studios]]\n* [[Bleecker Street (company)|Bleecker Street]]\n* Le Pacte\n* K5 International\n}}\n| released = {{Film date|2016|05|16|[[2016 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2016|11|17|Germany|2016|12|21|France|2016|12|28|United States}}\n| runtime = 118 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 117:46--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/paterson-film | title=''Paterson'' (15) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 9, 2016 | accessdate=November 9, 2016}}</ref>\n| country = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* Germany\n* France\n}}\n| language = English\n| budget = $5 million<ref name=NUM/>\n| gross = $10.8 million<ref name=NUM>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Paterson#tab=summary|title=Paterson (2016)|website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=February 10, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Paterson''''' is a 2016 [[drama film]] written and directed by [[Jim Jarmusch]]. The film stars [[Adam Driver]] as a bus driver and poet named Paterson, and [[Golshifteh Farahani]] as his wife, who dreams of being a country music star and opening a cupcake business.\n\n''Paterson'' was selected to compete for the [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[2016 Cannes Film Festival]], where it won the [[Palm Dog Award]].<ref name=\"IW\">{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/cannes-live-stream-2016-film-festival-lineup-list |title=2016 Cannes Film Festival Announces Lineup |accessdate=April 14, 2016 |work=IndieWire}}</ref><ref name=\"VarCannes\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/festivals/cannes-film-festival-official-selection-lineup-2016-1201753269/ |title=Cannes 2016: Film Festival Unveils Official Selection Lineup |accessdate=April 14, 2016 |work=Variety}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/palm-dog-award-2016-nellie-paterson-jim-jarmusch-cannes-20160520 |title=The 2016 Palm Dog Posthumously Awarded to Nellie, The Dog From Jim Jarmusch's 'Paterson' |date=May 20, 2016 |accessdate=May 20, 2016 |author=Vikram Murthi |work=Indiewire}}</ref> It was released in Germany on November 17, 2016, by K5 International; in France on December 21, 2016, by Le Pacte; and in the United States on December 28, 2016, by [[Amazon Studios]] and [[Bleecker Street (company)|Bleecker Street]].\n\n==Plot==\nThe film spans one week, beginning with Monday, in the life of Paterson, a bus driver in [[Paterson, New Jersey]]. Every day follows much the same pattern: Paterson gets up early and goes to work, where he listens to passengers talking and, during pauses, writes poetry in a notebook he carries with him. After work he walks Marvin, his wife's dog, and stops for a beer at Shades Bar, where he interacts with the other patrons and the owner, Doc ([[Barry Shabaka Henley]]).\n\nPaterson's wife, Laura, loves his poems and has long urged him to publish them or at least make copies. He finally promises to go to the copy shop on the weekend. But when Paterson and Laura come home from a movie Saturday night, they find that Marvin has shredded his notebook, destroying his poems.\n\nThe next day, a dejected Paterson goes for a walk and sits down at his favorite site, the [[Great Falls (Passaic River)|Great Falls of the Passaic River]]. There, a Japanese man ([[Masatoshi Nagase]]) takes a seat beside him and begins a conversation about poetry after Paterson notices that the man is reading the book-length poem ''[[Paterson (poem)|Paterson]]'' by [[William Carlos Williams]]. The man seems to know that Paterson himself is a poet even though he denies it and hands him a gift, an empty notebook. The film ends with Paterson writing a poem in his new notebook.\n\n==Cast==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Adam Driver]] as Paterson\n* [[Golshifteh Farahani]] as Laura\n* Nellie as Marvin\n* [[William Jackson Harper]] as Everett\n* Chasten Harmon as Marie\n* [[Barry Shabaka Henley]] as Doc\n* [[Rizwan Manji]] as Donny\n* [[Masatoshi Nagase]] as Japanese Poet\n* [[Kara Hayward]] as Female Student\n* [[Jared Gilman]] as Male Student\n* [[Method Man]] as Method Man\n* [[Sterling Jerins]] as Young Poet\n}}\n\n==Production==\nIn April 2014, it was announced that [[Jim Jarmusch]] would write and direct a film about a poet living in [[Paterson, New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2014/04/jim-jarmuschs-next-film-is-about-a-bus-driver-poet-in-paterson-new-jersey-87444/|title=Jim Jarmusch\u2019s Next Film Is About A Bus Driver & Poet In Paterson, New Jersey|website=[[Indiewire.com]]|first=Edward|last=Davis|date=April 4, 2014|accessdate=December 30, 2016}}</ref> In January 2016, it was revealed that [[Adam Driver]] and [[Golshifteh Farahani]] had been cast in the film, with Oliver Simon and Daniel Baur serving as executive producers under their K5 Film banner, while Joshua Astrachan and Carter Logan would produce under their Animal Kingdom and Inkjet banners respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/adam-driver-to-star-in-jim-jarmuschs-paterson-amazon-and-k5-to-co-finance-1201681250/|title=Adam Driver To Star In Jim Jarmusch\u2019s \u2018Paterson\u2019, Amazon And K5 To Co-Finance|first=Ali|last=Jafaar|date=January 13, 2016|accessdate=May 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe film was shot over 30 days in fall 2015, in [[Paterson, New Jersey]], and various locations in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/12/20th-century-women-paterson-toni-ehrmann-ocean-waves-specialty-box-office-preview-1201876275/|title=\u201920th Century Women\u2019 & \u2018Paterson\u2019 Join Year-End Awards-Season Fray \u2013 Specialty Preview|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Brian|last=Brooks|date=December 28, 2016|accessdate=December 30, 2016}}</ref> \n\nThe poet [[Ron Padgett]] provided the poems attributed to the character Paterson, while Jarmusch wrote the poem \"Water Falls\" attributed to a young girl in the film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jim Jarmusch, Ron Padgett and the sublime poetry of 'Paterson'|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-paterson-poetry-20170102-story.html|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> The film features four of Padgett's existing poems and three new poems written for the film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Poetry Stars in a Movie|url=https://www.poetryfoundation.org/features/audio/detail/92268|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n[[File:Cannes 2016 25.jpg|thumb|right|[[Adam Driver]], [[Golshifteh Farahani]] and [[Jim Jarmusch]] at the [[2016 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\nThe film had its world premiere on May 16, 2016, at the [[2016 Cannes Film Festival]], where it competed for the [[Palme d'Or]].<ref name=\"IW\"/><ref name=\"VarCannes\"/> [[Amazon Studios]] distributed the film in the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/01/12/casting-net-adam-driver-jim-jarmusch|title=Casting Net: Adam Driver joins Jim Jarmusch comedy Paterson|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Will|last=Robinson|date=January 12, 2016|accessdate=May 5, 2016}}</ref> It was later announced that [[Bleecker Street (company)|Bleecker Street]] was partnering with Amazon on releasing the film, on December 28, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/adam-driver-paterson-release-date-1201822050/|title=Adam Driver\u2019s \u2018Paterson\u2019 Gets Awards-Season Release Date (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Brent|last=Lang|date=July 25, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2016}}</ref> It was released in Germany on November 17, 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.impawards.com/2016/paterson_ver2_xlg.html|title=Paterson|website=IMP Awards|date=October 3, 2016|accessdate=October 3, 2016}}</ref> and in France on December 21, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.le-pacte.com/fileadmin/user_upload/pdf/line-up/line-up-fr.pdf|title=Le Pacte Line Up 2016|website=Le Pacte|accessdate=September 14, 2016}}</ref> It opened for a limited run in the eponymous city on January 27, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2017/01/paterson_movie_coming_to_paterson_adam_driver_jim.html#incart_river_home|title='Paterson' movie finally coming to Paterson|publisher=|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nOn review aggregator website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 96% based on 230 reviews, with an average rating of 8.5/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Paterson'' adds another refreshingly unvarnished entry to Jim Jarmusch's filmography\u2014and another outstanding performance to Adam Driver's career credits.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/paterson/|title=Paterson (2016)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=April 4, 2017}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 90 out of 100, based on 41 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/paterson|title=Paterson|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=September 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTodd McCarthy of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' gave the film a positive review, writing: \"A mild-mannered, almost startlingly undramatic work that offers discreet pleasures to longtime fans of the New York indie-scene veteran, who can always be counted on to go his own way.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/paterson-cannes-review-894268|title='Paterson': Cannes Review|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Todd|last=McCarthy|date=May 15, 2016|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref> Eric Kohn of ''[[Indiewire.com]]'' also gave the film a positive review, writing: \"But \"Paterson\" has too much clarity of mind to fall into a similar category. The story builds to an accidental circumstance that, on the surface, might not seem like a big deal\u2014but in the context of Paterson\u2019s tiny universe, resonates with tragic connotations. The brilliantly cryptic finale explores what it means to work back from personal setbacks to find a new source of inspiration. It\u2019s an apt statement from Jarmusch, a filmmaker who continues to surprise and innovate while remaining true to his singular voice, and who here seems to have delivered its purest manifestation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/05/cannes-review-adam-driver-stars-in-jim-jarmuschs-paterson-his-most-intimate-film-290526/|title=Cannes Review: Adam Driver Stars in Jim Jarmusch\u2019s \u2018Paterson,\u2019 His Most Intimate Film|website=[[Indiewire.com]]|first=Eric|last=Kohn|date=May 15, 2016|accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | List of awards and nominations\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Award\n! Date of ceremony\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n! Ref(s)\n|-\n| [[Belgian Film Critics Association]]\n| January 7, 2017\n| [[Grand Prix (Belgian Film Critics Association)|Grand Prix]]\n| ''Paterson''\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=\"Carol\" d\u00e9sign\u00e9 film de l'ann\u00e9e 2016 par les critiques belges|url=http://www.7sur7.be/7s7/fr/1528/Cinema/article/detail/3049421/2017/01/07/Carol-designe-film-de-l-annee-2016-par-les-critiques-belges.dhtml|work=7sur7|publisher=[[De Persgroep]]|date=January 7, 2017|accessdate=January 8, 2017|language=French}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Awards 2016|Boston Society of Film Critics Awards]]\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Awards 2016|December 11, 2016]]\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]]\n| [[Jim Jarmusch]]\n| {{draw|Runner-up}}\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/la-la-land-named-best-picture-by-boston-society-film-critics-955066 |title='La La Land' Named Best Picture by Boston Society of Film Critics |first=Patrick |last=Shanley |date=December 11, 2016 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=December 11, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Cannes Film Festival]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[2016 Cannes Film Festival|May 22, 2016]]\n| [[Palm Dog Award]]\n| Nellie <small>(posthumous award)</small>\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| <ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"IW\"/>\n|-\n| [[Palme d'Or]]\n| Jim Jarmusch\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Chicago Film Critics Association]]\n| [[Chicago Film Critics Association Awards 2016|December 15, 2016]]\n| [[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| [[Adam Driver]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chicagofilmcritics.org/component/content/article/148-cfca-nominees-2016 |title=The 2016 Chicago Film Critics Association Award Nominees |date=December 11, 2016 |publisher=[[Chicago Film Critics Association]] |accessdate=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[Gotham Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[Gotham Independent Film Awards 2016|November 28, 2016]]\n| Best Feature\n| ''Paterson''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"4\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/2016-gotham-independent-award-nominations/|title=2016 Gotham Independent Awards Nominations|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|date=October 20, 2016|accessdate=October 24, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Actor\n| Adam Driver\n